8. Authentication
Overview:
Smart-Meet uses JWT (JSON Web Tokens) for stateless authentication. The authentication flow is:

User submits registration or login form with credentials
Server validates credentials and generates a JWT token signed with JWT_SECRET
Token is returned to the client and stored in localStorage
For subsequent requests, the token is sent in the Authorization header as: Bearer <token>
The auth middleware on the server verifies the token and attaches the user to the request
Protected routes are only accessible with a valid token

Password Security:

Passwords are hashed using bcryptjs with 10 salt rounds
bcrypt.compare() is used for timing-attack resistant password comparison
Minimum password length of 6 characters enforced at the model level

Token Details:
PropertyValueAlgorithmHS256 (HMAC SHA-256)Expiry7 daysStoragelocalStorage on clientHeader formatAuthorization: Bearer token

